body.name: POINWER 850 Watt Power Supply 80 Plus Gold - Silent 12cm RGB Fan, Full Modular, Active PFC, 105°C Capacitor - High-Performance 850W PSU for Gaming & ATX Case Computers, 5 Year Warranty
features: ENERGY-EFFICIENT CERTIFIED: This 850 watt power supply 80 plus gold provides up to 91.8% super high power efficiency under typical loads. It reduces system heat and prolongs the lifespan of your computer while saving on your electricity bill.

PREMIUM CAPACITORS: This power supply 850w utilizes 100% High-Performance capacitors that withstand temperatures of up to 105°C. It guarantees superior power supply stability for your gaming and e-sports needs.
QUIET RGB FAN: Our 850w PSU features a 12cm silent fan that adjusts its speed according to temperature. With up to 9 RGB modes (26 color choices), it adds a vibrant atmosphere to your gaming setup.

ADVANCED SAFETY FEATURES: The 850 watt power supply has an active PFC that ensures 100V-240V wide voltage self-adaptive input, catering to voltage-unstable regions. It is equipped with an array of protection mechanisms: OVP/OCP/OPP/OTP/UVP/SCP.

FULL MODULAR & COMPATIBLE: The full modular power supply 850w utilizes only the necessary cables, reducing system clutter and improving airflow. It's compatible with various systems, including gaming consoles and ATX case computers.

How to: Connect a PSU to a 4-pin CPU port? If you want to connect our PSU into a 4-pin EPS motherboard port, simply pull the two halves of the 8-pin connector apart and connect one half into the motherboard port. Can you change the color of the fan? No, the color of the power supply fan changes automatically. It features 9 RGB modes with 26 pre-selected colors that cycle automatically. There is no option to customize the fan color settings. Does it come with 8 and 6 pin connectors for a gpu? Yes it has double connecters for 8pin and 6pin on the same cord. Will it fit in a ATX midtower pc build? Yes it should fit easily How do you get more cables and where do you buy them? Amazon sells extra Cables

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 20, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 3.0 out of 5 stars Not quite what they say but does the job
reviews.reviewText: Its a power supply that looks roughly like the photos but does not include the advertised 4 pin pc connector, no mounting holes for the included screws and the 80plus gold certification is nowhere on the box or product. Once the cables are sorted out, it seems to work as advertised. The fan moves a lot of air and make almost no noise. All my components power up and seem to work fine. My biggest complaint is that the LED lighting is obnoxiously bright, even on red. Since I can't mount it to my case, it sits on top, lighting the entire room up like some night club.

reviews.reviewTitle: Working good so far on older processor
reviews.reviewText: This is a non-modular 650W ATX 80+ Bronze power supply. Black in color, RBG LED fan. Non-modular as mentioned, so you have all your cables already attached to the rear.Fits perfectly in a new case where the power supply is hidden, so no cables are visible. If your power supply is visible, you may want to invest in a modular power supply.Easy to install. Fan runs pretty quiet.The price is right, the performance has been good so far. I have not run it too hard to test it for strain under load etc.The LEDs look good paired with other case lighting. If you're planning on putting this in a high performance pc, I would probably look at other options just for piece of mind.

This power supply has been powering an old 1080 mining bitcoin for the last two weeks or so and has been rock solid. It is silent (or at the very least silent relative to the gpu) and gets the job done. Normally I like creature comforts like semi modular cables which isn't present here butat this price for a bronze rated supply, I didn't think that was a reasonable ask anyways. Cables are sheathed and looks pretty clean.Personally, I don't have any complaints. I think this is quite a good value.

Received for unbiased review...This is an 80+ Bronze power supply (power efficiency rating). (Note: I found a peculiar problem with this power supply. If you happen to have a static discharge from your hand to the computer case, the power supply immediately shuts down instead of grounding out the discharge. This is bad for data protection, as your machine could shut off in the middle of writing data. It may be to protect your motherboard from back voltages, but it should protect the computer to a certain extent without having to cut all the power off. i had this happen while just trying to put the case cover back on the computer. As soon as the cover touched the rest of the case it immediately shut off. Complete shut off from touching the case has happened several times.)I ordered this for an older Intel Core 2 Quad 6550 system, and so far it has been fairly quiet. The temperature has not felt overly hot, and the fan has stayed at a steady low speed. The RGB fan looks really neat with its colour cycling. It isn't like my other 650 80+Gold of a different brand (which got transplanted to another computer) which doesn't run the fan at all until it needs to. I'm reducing a star because I could see the capacitor types through the grill, and they do not look like solid capacitors. This means lesser longevity, and less heat tolerance. I don't have an oscilloscope so I can't tell you how clean the power is. But so far, it is doing a good job. I always use a power supply that is much higher wattage than necessary for my builds to make sure it lasts. If you are using a system that isn't too demanding on power, a 650W capable power supply is a good purchase. It should give you a decent amount of overhead for a good graphics card (If you are going to be using a high end graphics card you should get a much higher wattage power supply and quality for longevity).

reviews.reviewTitle: It works ok but beware of the rats nest of cables
reviews.reviewText: I've had this running an i3 for the last week and so far not had any issues with it as far as performance goes.It's also powering a 1080, but neither the CPU nor GPU has been driven hard.The fan runs quiet, but I'm not a fan of RGB lighting. If I want to see that much colour, I'll set up Christmas lights in my room. There is no way to turn off the LEDs.Fortunately, the lights are at the rear, so they aren't that much of a distraction.The big problem here is that this is NOT a modular PSU. There is just one big bundle of cables that come out of it, which makes it messy when trying to control airflow. I don't like having a rat's nest of cables that need to be somehow tied back or moved to avoid blacking airflow. It's like stepping back into the late '90s when every PSU was set up this way. I'm not sure it's worth saving $20 instead of getting a brand name with modular cables.So performance-wise, it works well, but if you're one of those people who like RGB lightings and want to show off the innards of your tower, you probably won't like it because of the cables mucking things up.For anyone who's more into just powering up a PC and not concerned about what the inside looks like this will probably work.

The media could not be loaded. Aside from the packaging claiming that unit has modular cabling and multi-gpu support, I can confirm that is a non-modular unit; There is only a pair of 6+2 pin PCIe power connections running off a single cable which is enough for the majority of single GPU configurations. If you're on a really tight budget, this power supply can definitely get you up and running without much hassle.I appreciate the all black cabling as it can definitely blend in discreetly into a black framed computer tower; With this non-modular design, an ATX mid-tower case would be sufficient to manage the cable length; It might be more difficult with a smaller enclosure to find a place to stuff the excess cabling.The unit itself does come packaged with a protective black foam sleeve and you do get four cable ties along with four case screws; I do find the construction quite lightweight compared to other PSU units I've installed in previous systems. The fan is fairly quiet and stays spinning while the unit is on; It does have four independent LEDs which cycle colours at random intervals; There is no way to control the lighting for the unit nor sync it up any other additional lighting accessories.I do find that the sata power cables ending off with molex connections odd; I would have prefered sata power connections as the single endpoint and have the molex connections grouped together. For additional length for the fixed cables, you can definitely add a cable extension kit to reach the 8-pin EPS connection better on a motherboard.
